{"id":"1903.11544","submitter":"Sumati Surya","authors":"Sumati Surya","title":"The causal set approach to quantum gravity","comments":"Latex, 78 pages, 22 Figures. Invited review article for Living\n  Reviews in Relativity. Version 2 includes an Appendix with definitions and\n  abbreviations. Typos corrected and some discussions made clearer","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s41114-019-0023-1","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The causal set theory (CST) approach to quantum gravity postulates that at\nthe most fundamental level, spacetime is discrete, with the spacetime continuum\nreplaced by locally finite posets or \"causal sets\". The partial order on a\ncausal set represents a proto-causality relation while local finiteness encodes\nan intrinsic discreteness. In the continuum approximation the former\ncorresponds to the spacetime causality relation and the latter to a fundamental\nspacetime atomicity, so that finite volume regions in the continuum contain\nonly a finite number of causal set elements. CST is deeply rooted in the\nLorentzian character of spacetime, where a primary role is played by the causal\nstructure poset. Importantly, the assumption of a fundamental discreteness in\nCST does not violate local Lorentz invariance in the continuum approximation.\nOn the other hand, the combination of discreteness and Lorentz invariance gives\nrise to a characteristic non-locality which distinguishes CST from most other\napproaches to quantum gravity.\n  In this review we give a broad, semi-pedagogical introduction to CST,\nhighlighting key results as well as some of the key open questions. This review\nis intended both for the beginner student in quantum gravity as well as more\nseasoned researchers in the field.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 27 Mar 2019 16:53:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 28 Aug 2019 05:56:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-09"}
