{"id":"1903.11738","submitter":"Patrick Coles","authors":"Patrick J. Coles, M. Cerezo, Lukasz Cincio","title":"Strong bound between trace distance and Hilbert-Schmidt distance for\n  low-rank states","comments":"6 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 100, 022103 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.100.022103","report-no":"LA-UR-19-22724","categories":"quant-ph math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The trace distance between two quantum states, $\\rho$ and $\\sigma$, is an\noperationally meaningful quantity in quantum information theory. However, in\ngeneral it is difficult to compute, involving the diagonalization of $\\rho -\n\\sigma$. In contrast, the Hilbert-Schmidt distance can be computed without\ndiagonalization, although it is less operationally significant. Here, we relate\nthe trace distance and the Hilbert-Schmidt distance with a bound that is\nparticularly strong when either $\\rho$ or $\\sigma$ is low rank. Our bound is\nstronger than the bound one could obtain via the norm equivalence of the\nFrobenius and trace norms. We also consider bounds that are useful not only for\nlow-rank states but also for low-entropy states. Our results have relevance to\nquantum information theory, quantum algorithms design, and quantum complexity\ntheory.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Mar 2019 00:24:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 6 Aug 2019 17:17:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-08-07"}
